  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Girls STEAM Camp</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Improve policies, laws, regulations, and administrative practices affecting the private sector&apos;s ability to compete nationally and internationally. All the elements include not only the adoption and implementation of policies, but also their oversight by elected officials, NGOs, and the private sector. Improve the capacity of private sector entities to respond and link to markets. This Area includes work to link the poor to markets through effective and economically sustainable systems and relationships</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">This award strives to improve policies, laws, regulations, and administrative practices affecting the private sector&apos;s ability to compete nationally and internationally. More specifically, this award S/GP plans to grant $200,000 USD to a private sector organization to help implement a Girls STEAM camp in Rwanda. The camp is currently a partnership between S/GP, The Intel Foundation, Girl Up Campaign, and Microsoft 4Afrika Initiative. We anticipate allocating 1% towards administrative activities; Our private sector partners usually cover administrative costs in their cost share.The primary purpose of the camp is to address the strong gender imbalance that exists internationally in regards to women&apos;s presence in the STEM fields of science, technology, engineering and mathematics. The need to address this imbalance is especially prevalent in Sub-Saharan Africa, which continues to lag behind when it comes to gender equality in education and health. Strides have been made to decrease the gender gap in primary education, but the UN states in its 2013 Millennium Development Goals Report that the gap is increasing with older children as female enrollment rates drop at the secondary and tertiary levels.One area where Africa has made substantial progress in closing the gender gap is their political systems. A drastic increase in female government officials coupled with large impact investments by foreign corporations and the rapid expansion of IT to Africa indicate the time is now to address discrimination and bring more STEM-educated women into the global workforce.The goal is to empower young women with the knowledge and skillsets to be competitive against their male counterparts during a time of rapid, technological development, providing them with access to high-tech resources, like-minded peers, impactful business connections and inspiring mentors. The camp will bring a diverse group of 30 female U.S. high school students together in Africa for an opportunity to study alongside 70 African students in the summer of 2015. The student selection process will be jointly decided, and the application will open in December 2014..</narrative>
  </description>
